Photo by Bloomberg News
			In 2005, Claire's Stores Inc. celebrated 20 years as a publicly traded company; two years later, it went private.
		




Why Claire's is no jewel


Claire's Stores Inc. has grown to nearly 3,500 stores in the U.S. and abroad by selling costume jewelry to tweens who buy and discard $10 necklaces faster than they unfriend their friends. The value of the retailer's stock in its planned IPO�may be just as fleeting.�  The Hoffman Estates-based company has boosted sales nearly 16 percent over the past four years, to $1.56 billion, posted increased same-store sales in 10 of the past 13 quarters and expanded outside the U.S. The company's trendy product mix, ranging from $3.50 Jolly Rancher-flavored lip balm to $9.50 chandelier earrings, is allowance-friendly, and its purple signs are fixtures in most American malls.  “Claire's is very strong in the 10-to-14 age category,” says Neil Stern, a senior partner at Chicago retail consultancy McMillan Doolittle & Co. “They grab young customers because they do (ear) piercing, and they hold on to them until they hit freshman or sophomore year.” But that might not be enough to pay off the $2.4 billion debt that Claire's carries following its takeover by Apollo Management LP, a New York private-equity firm, in 2007. With weak cash flow and no access to investment-grade debt, the company is hoping a public offering will help retire $522 million in debt that comes due in 2015. “Claire's doesn't have many choices right now,” says Monica Aggarwal, a credit analyst at New York-based Fitch Ratings Inc.  If Claire's can pull off its IPO deal, it will underscore the market's increasing appetite for public offerings, particularly from companies sponsored by private-equity firms. It also would signify something of a resurrection of the retailer, which not long ago was expected to follow Linens "n Things Inc. (another Apollo purchase) into a leveraged-buyout grave.  But if anything goes wrong—say, teen spending weakens or competitors take away too much market share—Claire's could default on its loans or go bankrupt by 2016, according to a scenario explored in a recent Standard & Poor's note.  Claire's, which was debt-free prior to Apollo's purchase, turned in $189 million in profit on sales of $1.48 billion in 2006, its last year as a public company. By 2012, net income totaled just $6 million on sales of $1.56 billion, as the company shoveled $206 million toward interest payments. With debt that stands at about eight times its annual earnings, Claire's is the most highly leveraged of 25 retail and consumer companies followed by Fitch.
PAYING DOWN DEBT
Other retail and consumer companies have used proceeds from an IPO to pay down debt, though none was as leveraged as Claire's.  When nutrition store operator GNC Holdings Inc., formerly also owned by Apollo, went public in 2011, it used $240 million in net proceeds, combined with cash on hand, to pay down about $520 million of its $900 million in debt. Today, GNC's stock is up to more than $45, a whopping 184 percent above its $16 debut, and same-store sales are improving markedly.
quote|If Claire's can pull off its IPO, it will underscore the market's increasing appetite for public offerings.
One difference is that Pittsburgh-based GNC actually had some cash on hand. Claire's cash flow, on the other hand, dwindled to $15 million in 2012, down from $32 million in 2011 and $103 million in 2010. In March, Standard & Poor's cut the company's debt rating to deep junk territory. New York-based S&P analyst David Kuntz predicts that Claire's “substantially leveraged capital structure with very thin cash flow” is unlikely to change in the coming year, despite the possibility of a slight increase in same-store sales. Claire's has another problem, Mr. Stern says: It has carpeted North America with nearly 2,000 stores in 88 percent of domestic malls. For substantial growth, the company must look overseas. The company has 1,161 stores in Europe and tested the Chinese market last year, with three stores. It says it will open 150 company-owned stores globally in 2013 and explore Brazil, Russia and Australia via franchises.  The company also faces tougher competition from apparel retailers Forever 21 and H&M, which sell accessories for as low as $5, and rapidly expanding upstarts. They include Francesca's Holdings Corp., which opened 76 Francesca's Collections jewelry boutiques across the U.S. in 2012 and increased sales more than 45 percent to $296 million, and Charming Charlie Inc., which opened 60 locations last year. Despite the uncertainties, Apollo says it's time to cash out. “We're selling everything not nailed down,” Apollo Chairman and CEO Leon Black said at an investment conference in Los Angeles this month.


